# Why Did the Central Powers Lose World War I?

## Executive Summary

The Central Powers, consisting primarily of Germany, Austria-Hungary, the Ottoman Empire, and Bulgaria, were defeated in World War I due to a combination of strategic missteps, economic hardships, and the entry of the United States into the war. Key factors included the failure of military strategies like the Schlieffen Plan, the effective naval blockade by the Allies, and the internal collapse of the Central Powers' economies and political structures. The Allied Powers, bolstered by fresh American troops and resources, were able to outlast and outmaneuver the Central Powers, leading to their eventual surrender in 1918.

