## Detailed Findings

1. **Strategic and Tactical Failures**: The Central Powers made several strategic errors, notably the failure of the Schlieffen Plan, which aimed to quickly defeat France before turning to Russia. This plan underestimated the resistance from Belgium and the speed of Russian mobilization, leading to a prolonged two-front war[^1]. "The failure of the famous Schlieffen Plan, came as a great blow to Germany, which changed the entire chain of events which were forthcoming"[^2].

2. **Economic and Resource Shortages**: The British naval blockade severely restricted the Central Powers' access to essential resources, leading to widespread shortages and civilian hardship. "The British Blockade was one of the key factors in the defeat of Germany and her allies... Germanyâ€™s imports had fallen by 55% of pre-war import levels"[^3].

3. **Entry of the United States**: The entry of the United States into the war in 1917 provided the Allies with fresh troops and resources, significantly boosting their morale and capabilities. "The United States were able to support the Allied front with a million fresh soldiers, this greatly improved Allied morale and demoralize the Germans and her allies further"[^4].

